Section 2 - Relationship between the gcc_spending and energy_spending

In the next step, we are going to investigate the relationship between the gcc_spending and energy_spending. The data is generated from different department. Therefore we cannot combine these two data sets with department. Instead, we combine them with year. We want to investigate whether gcc_spending and energy_spending are related across the year. The plot below shows the relationship.

We can see from the plot that the data does not show a specific relationship between the two variables. We aslo run a regression with these two variables and the below are the regression results. The r-square is 2.202563910^{-5}, which is pretty low. The p-value is 0.5132995, which does not indicate any relationship between the variables. It makes sense because the gcc_spedning and energy_spending data come from different departments. We only combine them by year.

Section 3 - Relationship between rd_budget and gcc_spending

Since we cannot find the relationship between the energy_spedning and gcc_spending with different departments across the year. In the next step, we will work on the data set with same departments across the year. We combine the federal R&D data with climate data by deparment and year. The plot below shows the relationship between rd_budget and gcc_spending for three departments - NASA,NSF,and Interior.The plot shows that as the rd_budget increases, the gcc_spending also increases.

We take a closer look at the relationship by seperating the years.

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = FEC$rd_budget ~ FEC$gcc_spending)
## 
## Residuals:
##        Min         1Q     Median         3Q        Max 
## -3.621e+09 -1.258e+09 -6.111e+08  1.488e+09  3.251e+09

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.498e+09 on 52 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9113, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9096 
## F-statistic: 534.1 on 1 and 52 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The plots show the relationship between rd_budget and gcc_spending in different years. They show that these two variables are positive related even in different years. We then run a regression between these two variables. The regression summary is provided above and the r-square is 0.9112804 and p-value is 5.125756210^{-29}. The r-square is 0.9112804, which is pretty high, and the p-value 5.125756210^{-29} also indicates that the relationship is significant. The coefficient is 7.7153832, whose magnitude is positive. In this section, we conclude that rd_budget is positively related with gcc_spending.

Section 4 What drive GDP?

We plan to run a regression on these variables. From section 3 we know that rd_budget is highly positively realted to gcc_spending. In this case we will ignore the rd-budget.
